  {
    "objectID": "lecture5-correlation.html#the-correlation-coefficient",
    "href": "lecture5-correlation.html#the-correlation-coefficient",
    "title": "",
    "section": "The correlation coefficient",
    "text": "The correlation coefficient\n\nThe correlation coefficient, \\(r\\), measures the strength of the linear association between two quantitative variables;\n\n\n\nThe correlation coefficient is always between -1 and 1:\n\nPositive correlation: an increase in \\(X\\) tends to be followed by an increase in \\(Y\\);\nNegative correlation: an increase in \\(X\\) tends to be followed by an decrease in \\(Y\\);"
  },
  {
    "objectID": "lecture5-correlation.html#properties-of-correlation",
    "href": "lecture5-correlation.html#properties-of-correlation",
    "title": "",
    "section": "Properties of Correlation",
    "text": "Properties of Correlation\n\n\n\\(r\\) has no unit;\n\\(r=-1\\) for perfect negative correlation\n\\(r=1\\) for perfect positive correlation\n\\(r\\approx 0\\) implies very weak or no linear relationship between the variables;\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nWarning\n\n\n\\(r\\) close to zero does not imply two variables are not related. They could still have a non-linear relationship."
  },
  {
    "objectID": "lecture5-correlation.html#example",
    "href": "lecture5-correlation.html#example",
    "title": "",
    "section": "Example",
    "text": "Example\n\nn = 1000;\nx = \n{\n  const values = Array(n);\n  for (let i = 0; i < n; i++){\n    values[i] = Math.random() * (900 - 300) + 300;\n  }\n  return values;\n}\nmean_x = x.reduce((a,b) => a+b, 0) / n;\nvx = x.reduce((a,b) => a+(b-mean_x)**2/(n-1), 0);\n\nnoise = \n{\n  const values = Array(n);\n  for (let i = 0; i < n; i++){\n    values[i] = Math.random() * 2 - 1;\n  }\n  \n  const mean_noise = values.reduce((a,b) => a+b, 0) / n;\n  const vnoise = values.reduce((a,b) => a+(b-mean_noise)**2/(n-1), 0);\n  return values.map(item => {\n    return (item - mean_noise)/Math.sqrt(vnoise);\n  });\n}\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n// Create the interactive bars for size and variability\n\nviewof corr_bar = Inputs.range([-1, 1], \n                           {value: 0,\n                            step: 0.0001, \n                            label: \"Correlation Coefficient: \"});\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nslope = {\n  if (corr_bar != 1 && corr_bar != -1){\n    return Math.sign(corr_bar) * Math.sqrt(corr_bar**2/(vx * (1-corr_bar**2)));\n  }\n  else {\n    return Math.sign(corr_bar) * .1;\n  }\n}\n\ny = \n{\n  const values = Array(n);\n  for (let i = 0; i<n; i++){\n   // values[i] = slope * x[i] + noise[i] * Math.sqrt(slope**2 * vx * (1 - corr_bar**2)/corr_bar**2)\n   if (corr_bar != 1 && corr_bar != -1){\n     values[i] = slope * x[i] + noise[i];\n   }\n   else {\n     values[i] = slope * x[i];\n   }\n  }\n  return values;\n}\n\ndata = \n{\n  const values = Array(n);\n  for (let i = 0; i<n; i++){\n    values[i] = {'x': x[i], 'y': y[i]};\n  }\n  return values;\n}\n\n\nPlot.plot({\n  inset: 8,\n  grid: false,\n  marks: [\n    Plot.dot(data, {x: \"x\", y: \"y\"})\n  ],\n  x: {\n    ticks: 0,\n    tickSize: 0,\n    line: true,\n    labelAnchor: \"center\"\n  },\n  y: {\n    ticks: 0,\n    tickSize: 0,\n    line: true,\n    labelAnchor: \"center\"\n  }\n});"
  },
  {
    "objectID": "lecture5-correlation.html#correlation-is-not-causality",
    "href": "lecture5-correlation.html#correlation-is-not-causality",
    "title": "",
    "section": "Correlation is not causality",
    "text": "Correlation is not causality\n\nEven if there is an association (linear or otherwise) between two variables, it does not necessarily mean that one variable causes the other.\n\n\n\nThere could be a third variable, referred to as lurking variable, that causes both, \\(X\\) and \\(Y\\).\nAssociation is does not imply causation!"
  },
